Introduction

The idea of this project came from a converstation that I had with a Lyft driver a couple of weeks ago. During my travel, the driver mentioned that she also works for Uber and for some reason users of one of the apps pay way more tip compare to the others! This stroke me as a surprise and wondered if the amount of tip that a person pays can be predicted. This information can be useful to both the company (and perhaps the driver) as well as the user of the service. To analyze the amount of tip tha people pay, I have selected the NYC yellow taxi dataset from Jan 2017. It has more than 9 million instances and has enough features to be able to obtain meaningful patterns from it.

nyc_df <- read.csv('yellow_tripdata_2017-01.csv', colClasses = col_classes)
nyc_df <- nyc_df %>% mutate(tip_percent = ifelse(fare_amount > 0 & tip_amount >= 0 & tip_amount < fare_amount, round(tip_amount * 100 / fare_amount, 0), NA))
#making better use of provided times
useful_times <- function(data) { # transformation function for extracting some date and time features
  weekday_labels <- c('Sun', 'Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat')
  cut_levels <- c(1, 5, 9, 12, 16, 18, 22)
  hour_labels <- c('1AM-5AM', '5AM-9AM', '9AM-12PM', '12PM-4PM', '4PM-6PM', '6PM-10PM', '10PM-1AM')
  
  pickup_datetime <- ymd_hms(data$tpep_pickup_datetime)
  pickup_hour <- addNA(cut(hour(pickup_datetime), cut_levels))
  #adding NA as a category since 22 to 1 is not defined.
  #Then label it correctly as follows
  levels(pickup_hour) <- hour_labels
  pickup_day <- factor(wday(pickup_datetime), levels = 1:7, labels = weekday_labels)
  #wday starts with Sunday as day 1 (as opposed to Monday!)
  
  dropoff_datetime <- ymd_hms(data$tpep_dropoff_datetime)
  dropoff_hour <- addNA(cut(hour(dropoff_datetime), cut_levels))
  levels(dropoff_hour) <- hour_labels
  dropoff_day <- factor(wday(dropoff_datetime), levels = 1:7, labels = weekday_labels)
  
  data$pickup_hour <- pickup_hour
  data$pickup_day <- pickup_day
  data$dropoff_hour <- dropoff_hour
  data$dropoff_day <- dropoff_day
  data$trip_duration_sec <- as.integer(as.duration(dropoff_datetime - pickup_datetime))
  data
}
nyc_df <- useful_times(nyc_df)

Here’s the plot of the proportion of pick-ups for each time interval across days of the week.

hour_day_table <- table(nyc_df$pickup_day, nyc_df$pickup_hour)
library(lattice)
levelplot(prop.table(hour_day_table, 2), cuts = 20, xlab = "", ylab = "", main = "Distribution of taxis by day of week")

Besides the obvious that Saturday nights i.e. Sunday 1-5AM has the highest number of pick-ups as expected, Tuesday’s are particularly busier compare to the rest of week espcially in the morning from 5 to 9 AM. This might be because people have already put the Monday blues behind and want to push through the week motivated.

Outliers

Identifying outliers can sometimes be subjective and require extra information from the source of data. However in this case, things such as negative fare amount or more than 5 passengers are very suspicious. Here we showed records that have at least one of the followings: negative or more than 50 miles trip distance, zero or more than five passengers or lastly negative fare amount. The plot demonstrates these dubious records (350947 instances) that has more than a 50 mile trip and whether or not this trip happened in less than 10 minutes!

odd_trips <- nyc_df %>% filter((trip_distance > 50 | trip_distance <= 0) |
                                 (passenger_count > 5 | passenger_count == 0) |
                                 (fare_amount > 200 | fare_amount <= 0))
odd_trips %>% filter(trip_distance > 50) %>% ggplot() -> p
p + geom_histogram(aes(x = fare_amount, fill = (less_than_10 = trip_duration_sec <= 10*60)), binwidth = 10) +
  xlim(0, 500) + coord_fixed(ratio = 25) + xlab('Fare Amount in Dollars')

rm(odd_trips)

Adding Boroughs

In the latest available dataset (2017), pick up and drop off locations are identified by an ID. A separate csv file, howevere, is provided that specifies the zones and boroughs for each id. We merge the two datasets. The following table shows the number of trips between boroughs.

Since the trips from Manhattan to Manhattan takes the bulk of the data, we focus on Manhattan for now.

The following the tip brackets for all locations.

tip_brackets <- mht_df %>% select(c('PULocationID', 'DOLocationID', 'tip_color')) %>%

tip_brackets %>%
  ggplot(aes(PULocationID, DOLocationID)) +

One interesting thing for instance that can be seen from this plot is that people who go from location 243 (i.e. Washington Heights North Zone) to location 148 (i.e. Lower East Side) on average pay 0 tips but for the reverse trip pay between 15 to 20 percents!

The following plot shows the fare dollar amount per minute for each day and hour as well as tip percentage that poeple pay on average for each time slot.

testing <- mht_df %>% group_by(pickup_day, pickup_hour) %>%
  mutate(counts = n(), fare_per_min = fare_amount/(trip_duration_sec/60)) %>%
  select(c('pickup_day','pickup_hour','fare_per_min', 'counts','tip_percent'))

testing <- testing %>% group_by(pickup_day, pickup_hour) %>%
  mutate(fare_per_min = mean(fare_per_min), tip_percent = mean(tip_percent)) %>% distinct()

ggplot(testing, aes(pickup_day, pickup_hour)) + 
  geom_tile(aes(fill = fare_per_min), colour = "white") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1)) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "steelblue") +
  geom_text(aes(label = sprintf('%dK riders\n (%d%% tip)', signif(counts/1000, 2), round(tip_percent, 0))), size = 2.5) + 
  coord_fixed(ratio = .9)

We can see that from 1 to 5 am during the week people consistantly pay less tip. Also from 4 to 10 pm i.e. after work, people seems to be more generous compare to the other times of the week days. During the week, later at night i.e. from 10 pm to 5 am, fare amount per minute is clearly higher. This can perhaps be due to light traffic, however, this different is less obvious over the weekends.

Fitting an actual model

For this section, I considered using random forest (RF) to predict the tip percentage.

After splitting the data into two subsets namely trianing and test, we need to reduce the number of categories for location ids. This is because RF in r cannot handle more than 53 levels for categorical variable. For this reason, we sorted the data based on the number of records for each location and then merge the smallest counts into one group called ‘Rest’. Next, I’m planning to tune the model and in future consider other boroughs and perhaps different months to see if there’s consistant trends across months.
